content:
Learn how to integrate WSO2’s modern Identity and Access Management (IAM) solution into your React App.

3 min read
1 hour ago

--

In today’s digital landscape, securing your web applications is more critical than ever. Building an authentication system from scratch can be time-consuming and risky. This is where WSO2 Asgardeo, a powerful Identity as a Service (IDaaS) solution, comes in.
In this guide, I will walk you through integrating WSO2 Asgardeo into a React single-page application (SPA) to handle user authentication seamlessly.
Prerequisites
Before we begin, make sure you have:

• Node.js installed on your machine.

• A basic understanding of React.

• A free account on WSO2 Asgardeo.
Step 1: Configuring WSO2 Asgardeo
First, we need to register our application in the Asgardeo console.

• Log in to your Asgardeo Console.

• Navigate to Applications and click + New Application.

• Select Single Page Application and provide a name (e.g., React-Asgardeo-App).

• Set the Authorized Redirect URL to your local development server (usually http://localhost:5173 if you are using Vite).

• Once created, go to the Protocol tab and copy your Client ID. You will need this later!
Step 2: Setting Up the React Project
Let’s create a fast React application using Vite and install the official Asgardeo React SDK.
Open your terminal and run:
npm create vite@latest my-asgardeo-app -- --template react
cd my-asgardeo-app
npm install
npm install @asgardeo/auth-react react-router-domStep 3: Integrating the Asgardeo SDK
To use Asgardeo across our application, we need to wrap our root component with the AuthProvider provided by the SDK.
Open your main.jsx (or index.js) and update it with your configuration:
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App.jsx';
import { AuthProvider } from "@asgardeo/auth-react";const config = {
signInRedirectURL: "http://localhost:5173",
signOutRedirectURL: "http://localhost:5173",
clientID: "YOUR_CLIENT_ID_HERE", // Replace with your copied Client ID
baseUrl: "https://api.asgardeo.io/t/your_org_name", // Replace with your organization name
scope: [ "openid", "profile" ]
};
ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root')).render(
<React.StrictMode>
<AuthProvider config={config}>
<App />
</AuthProvider>
</React.StrictMode>,
)
(Make sure to replace the placeholder values with your actual Asgardeo credentials).
Step 4: Building the Authentication UI
Now, let’s create a simple UI to handle Login, Logout, and display user details. The @asgardeo/auth-react SDK gives us a handy useAuthContext hook to manage the authentication state.
Update your App.jsx:
import { useAuthContext } from "@asgardeo/auth-react";
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";function App() {
const { state, signIn, signOut, getBasicUserInfo } = useAuthContext();
const [userInfo, setUserInfo] = useState(null);
useEffect(() => {
if (state.isAuthenticated) {
getBasicUserInfo().then((info) => {
setUserInfo(info);
}).catch(console.error);
}
}, [state.isAuthenticated, getBasicUserInfo]);
return (
<div style={{ textAlign: "center", padding: "50px", fontFamily: "sans-serif" }}>
<h1>WSO2 Asgardeo React App 🔐</h1>
{state.isAuthenticated ? (
<div>
<h2>Welcome to your Dashboard! 🎉</h2>
<p><strong>Username:</strong> {state.username}</p>
{userInfo && <p><strong>Email:</strong> {userInfo.email}</p>}
<button onClick={() => signOut()} style={{ padding: "10px 20px", background: "red", color: "white", border: "none", borderRadius: "5px", cursor: "pointer" }}>
Logout
</button>
</div>
) : (
<div>
<p>Please log in to continue.</p>
<button onClick={() => signIn()} style={{ padding: "10px 20px", background: "#ff5000", color: "white", border: "none", borderRadius: "5px", cursor: "pointer" }}>
Login with Asgardeo
</button>
</div>
)}
</div>
);
}
export default App;
